      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In a letter to the editor on June 3, the executive director of Riverkeeper characterizes the spent fuel pool buildings located at the Indian Point nuclear plant as ''butler shacks.''</p>
        <p>In fact, the spent fuel is secured in federally monitored pools surrounded by six feet of concrete, built into solid bedrock, covered by more than 23 feet of water and protected by one of the best-trained private security forces in the United States.</p>
        <p>The real problem with the debate over the continued safe operation of Indian Point is that while the electricity, taxes and jobs are critically needed by most people within the region, the wealthy few behind Riverkeeper's continued assault on the site could care less.</p>
        <p>Because it does not emit greenhouse gases -- like carbon monoxide -- nuclear power is an environmentally sound technology for heavily polluted regions like New York City.</p>
        <p>LAURENCE P. GOTTLIEB  White Plains, June 3, 2003</p>
        <p>The writer is director of communications, Entergy Nuclear Northeast, which owns Indian Point.</p>
      </block>
